We have recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the following:

For the Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of closing the balances of RPT/SET Receivables and their corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income accounts, which represent the uncollected tax delinquencies, at yearend for the fair presentation in the financial statements; 

For the Treasury office to make separate reports for payments regarding tax delinquencies and advance payments since these shall be presented differently in the financial statements, and to reflect actual balances; 

Should there be payments in excess of the original amount recorded for RPT/SET Receivables, the List of Taxpayers prepared by the Treasury office may be revisited and revised since the excess payments indicate that the amounts therein may be underestimated/ undervalued. 

For the advance payments to be properly recorded through a credit to Deferred RPT/SET income accounts and the collection of payments in excess of the original amount to be recognized through a direct credit to RPT/SET Income accounts.

The Inventory Committee to review and revise the 2024 RPCPPE and all related reports to accurately reflect the results of the physical inventory, particularly by excluding items identified as “missing” from the “On Hand Per Count” column to ensure the correctness of reported data;
The concerned offices to conduct an immediate investigation to determine the circumstances surrounding the missing PPE items and identify the accountable officers or personnel, in accordance with existing property accountability rules and regulations.
The failure of the Accounting Office and the GSO to reconcile the PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively, as required under Section 266 of the GAM for LGUs, Volume I, resulted in unresolved variances between the two sets of records. This non-reconciliation casts doubt on the accuracy of the reported PPE balances, including related depreciation and accumulated depreciation, affecting the fair presentation of the financial statements, contrary to Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1.
We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO to reconcile the PPE ledger cards and property cards periodically;
Semi-expendable properties totaling ₱11,649,988.05 remained recorded under PPE accounts, contrary to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2022-004. This resulted in an overstatement of the PPE (gross) account by the same amount, along with corresponding misstatements in the depreciation and accumulated depreciation accounts. Consequently, the accuracy and fair presentation of the financial statements were impaired, contrary to Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1.
We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
Municipal Accountant to reclassify PPEs not meeting the capitalization threshold and make the necessary correcting entries following the change in accounting policy in compliance with COA Circular No. 2022-004;
Municipal Accountant to restate the comparative figures (CY 2023) in the Financial Statements as required in Item 4.6 of COA Circular 2022-004; and
The General Services Officer to reclassify PPE items that do not meet the capitalization threshold as semi-expendable properties and update the related reports accordingly, particularly the RPCPPE.

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to implement stricter budgetary controls and ensure that disbursements EME do not exceed the 2% threshold of Basic Real Property Tax (RPT) collections from the next preceding year, as prescribed under Section 325(h) of RA 7160.
Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to stop proposing EME S appropriations for offices other than the Office of the Mayor;
Direct all concerned offices to classify expenditures correctly in accordance with the Chart of Accounts prescribed by the Commission on Audit, and to avoid charging unrelated or ineligible expenses under the EME account.

We have reiterated our previous audit recommendation and the Municipal Mayor agreed to enjoin the HRMO the following:

To stipulate in the contract of service, specific highly technical duties and responsibilities that requires skills/ expertise and compare those against their actual outputs/ accomplishments to ascertain whether or not they are able to deliver their functions expected, otherwise the hiring is unjustified;

Stop the practice of hiring consultants for tasks which do not require expertise and that can be performed by the regular employees to avoid incurrence of additional expenditure disadvantageous to the agency; 

Identify those consultants whose scope of work overlap with the functions of the other consultants because it is an indication that there is a need to reduce their number in order to avoid wastage of public funds; and

Require the consultants to submit curriculum vitae and other relevant information that would support their credentials and eligibilities in their chosen field of expertise and for the management to create a databank of the consultants’ credentials/qualifications in order to determine whether their accomplishments are conformable to their qualifications and to justify their appointment as consultants.

We have recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to enjoin the management to adhere with the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 and Manual on Disposal of Government Property on the disposition procedures for PPE, viz:

For the Accounting office and the Inventory Committee to reconcile the inventory count per Report of Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) with property and accounting records, and accomplish the procedures required such as submission of disposal documents, inspection, appraisal, and determination of modes of disposal, before derecognition/ dropping of PPEs from Books of Accounts; 

The General Services Office/ Inventory Committee to prepare Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for all PPEs found unserviceable, obsolete and/or no longer needed;

For PPEs classified as non-existing or missing and of those without available records of accountability, the management should conduct the procedures enumerated under Items 7 and 8 of the same COA Circular for the disposition and derecognition; 

For the Accounting Office to keep as permanent file, the Registry of Derecognized PPEs as well as the copy of the approved request for derecognition and its supporting documents, and provide appropriate disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements; and

To implement the guidelines and procedures on the disposition of non-existing or missing PPE items for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts.

