We have recommended the management the following:

For the concerned officials and employees to settle immediately their unliquidated cash advances. Failure to do so would warrant the filing of malversation case against the erring officials/employees under Article 217;


Withhold the salaries and other emoluments in full of officials and employees who are still in service effective immediately and apply the said withheld amounts in their respective outstanding cash advances;



For the HRMO to enjoin the former Vice Mayor to sign authorization letter to deduct the outstanding cash advances from his terminal pay; and



In the case of the unliquidated cash advance of the deceased accountable officers, legal advice should be sought on how the LGU could impose the settlement of the cash advance through their heirs.

We have recommended the management the following:

To create Municipal Screening Committee for strict screening of student applicants, and ensuring that only qualified students avail the scholarship program and only the necessary expenses relative to their respective courses were being charged against the fund pursuant to the Resolution. They should also coordinate with the Barangay Officials regarding background checks of applicants, and to assure that the scholars are still enrolled;

To maintain database of the scholars’ courses, universities, year level and semester, as well as their general averages and grades for each semester to assure that the students met the standards set by the guidelines;


For the Municipal Accountant to check and verify whether all claims charged against the fund are essential to the courses/ studies of the scholars; and


For the management to demand the refund of the unnecessary and illegal claims of the erring official.

For the Accounting office to prepare and maintain subsidiary ledger for each kind of PPE owned by the municipality;
For the Inventory Committee to complete the physical inventory count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (RPCPPE); and also require the submission of the report to the requiring offices within the prescribed period; and
For the Inventory Committee and Accounting office to reconcile the differences, if any, between the physical inventory report and the general ledger balance of each PPE account; subsequently, the Accountant shall identify if the difference represents PPE that are still existing, no longer existing but with pertinent records, or no longer existing and without pertinent records. The conduct of property disposal shall be coursed thru the guidelines/procedures under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

For the Treasury Office to devise plans and strategies on how to facilitate the preparation of Certified List of Taxpayers; and coordinate their records with Municipal Assessor;
Subsequently, a report on RPT delinquencies must be prepared by the Treasury Office and impose penalties and avail remedies set by laws to compel the delinquent taxpayers to pay their taxes on time; and
submit the Certified List of Taxpayers to the Municipal Accountant to determine the accurate amount for the set-up of RPT and SET receivables at the beginning of the year.

To exhaust all means possible to determine the balances accruing to the prior years’ unspent balances of LDRRM fund, and 20% Development Fund. The Accounting office should coordinate with the Treasury office and other offices to retrieve and review all reports pertaining to the budget and utilization of LDRRM Fund and its Investment Plan, as well as that of 20% Development Plan for prior years in order to determine the unutilized balances for each year;
For the Accounting office to maintain subsidiary ledgers for unspent LDRRM Fund, 20% Development Fund, and all other accounts; and
To disclose in their Notes to Financial Statements the balances and details of the Trust Liability – DRRM for each year. It must be noted that any unutilized amount after five years shall be reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund and shall be made available for other social services after subsequent enactment by the local sanggunian.

For the concerned officials and employees to settle immediately their unliquidated cash advances. Failure to do so would warrant the filing of malversation case against the erring officials/employees under Article 217;
Withhold the salaries and other emoluments in full of officials and employees who are still in service effective immediately and apply the said withheld amounts in their respective outstanding cash advances;
For the HRMO to enjoin the former Vice Mayor to sign authorization letter to deduct the outstanding cash advances from his terminal pay; and
In the case of the unliquidated cash advance of the deceased accountable officers, legal advice should be sought on how the LGU could impose the settlement of the cash advance through their heirs.

